# Agent hook — `on-after-spec-pr-merged`

This is an **agent-form** lifecycle hook. Unlike the executable `on-<event>` shell
hook (a deterministic script, JSON in/out), an agent hook is a set of natural-language
instructions that the **merge-pr workflow's Hooks phase runs as an agent** — with full
tool access (`gh`, `git`, `node`, the task-source CLI, …). Use it for work a shell
script can't reasonably do: drafting prose, deciding based on diff content, opening a
follow-up, posting a richer ticket/PR comment.

## Activate

Copy this file to the active name (drop the `.example`) and edit:

```sh
cp openspec/hooks/on-after-spec-pr-merged.agent.md.example \
   openspec/hooks/on-after-spec-pr-merged.agent.md
```

The runner looks for `openspec/hooks/on-<event>.agent.md` exactly. It runs **after** the
deterministic lifecycle step (ticket comment + status + the `on-<event>` shell hook), so
anything here is additive. It is **best-effort** — a failure is logged and never un-does
the merge.

## Context you're given

The runner passes you: the `change` slug, the `event`, the merged PR number + URL, and
the merge SHA. Read `openspec/changes/<change>/.task-link.json` for the linked ticket id
and source.

## Your task (edit me)

> The spec contract for **{change}** just merged (PR #{prNumber}, `{mergeSha}`).
>
> 1. Read the merged delta spec under `openspec/changes/{change}/specs/` and write a
>    2–3 sentence plain-language summary of what the contract now guarantees.
> 2. Post that summary as a comment on the linked ticket using the task-source CLI:
>    `node .claude/workflows/lib/task-sources/cli.js comment <taskId> --text "<summary>"`
>    (skip if the change has no `.task-link.json`).
> 3. Return a one-line `summary` of what you did.

Keep side effects idempotent — this may run more than once if a merge is retried.
